data.content:
Good news: **this code has no `Thread.Abort` calls**, so there's nothing to migrate on that front. It uses `Start`, `Join`, and `Sleep`, all of which work fine in .NET 8.

That said, for a .NET 8 migration, the idiomatic improvement is replacing raw `Thread` usage with `Task`-based parallelism:

```csharp
public class SimpleWorker
{
    public async Task RunBatchAsync(List<WorkItem> items)
    {
        var tasks = items.Select(item => Task.Run(() => Process(item)));
        await Task.WhenAll(tasks);
    }

    private void Process(WorkItem item)
    {
        item.Result = ComputeResult(item.Input);
    }
}
```

**Key `Thread.Abort` migration tips** (for when you do encounter it elsewhere):

| .NET Framework | .NET 8 Replacement |
|---|---|
| `Thread.Abort()` | `CancellationToken` + cooperative cancellation |
| `ThreadAbortException` catch blocks | Remove — the exception no longer exists |
| `Thread.ResetAbort()` | Remove entirely |
| `Thread.Sleep()` in async code | `await Task.Delay(ms, token)` |

If you find `Thread.Abort` in other files, the pattern is:

```csharp
// Before (.NET Framework)
thread.Abort();

// After (.NET 8) — cooperative cancellation
var cts = new CancellationTokenSource();
await Task.Run(() => Process(item, cts.Token), cts.Token);
cts.Cancel(); // request cancellation

private void Process(WorkItem item, CancellationToken token)
{
    token.ThrowIfCancellationRequested();
    item.Result = ComputeResult(item.Input);
}
```

